<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n38223b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38223b">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38223b"> 223(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> shikk / (split one)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Janshah, the young Prince, no sooner comes to man&apos;s estate than he loses himself out hunting and falls in with cannibals whose bodies divide longitudinally, each moiety going its own way: these are the <mark>Shikk (split ones)</mark> which the Arabs borrowed from the Persian N&iacute;m-chihrah or Half-faces. <small> Richard F. Burton, &ldquo;Terminal Essay&rdquo;, <a name="RBTE1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#RBTE1"><cite title="source">The Book of the Thousand Nights and a Night</cite></a> (n.d.) X, 131</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: <cite>FW</cite> 191.1: &lsquo; [&hellip;] will you for the love of Sheekspair just help mine with the epithet?&rsquo; The motif of splitting, of which the Shikk provide only one model, recurs in the <i>Wake</i> and probably deserves separate study. It is variously applied to physical bodies (<cite>FW</cite> 121.17, <cite>FW</cite> 228.5, <cite>FW</cite> 231.15, <cite>FW</cite> 253.34, <cite>FW</cite> 454.8) or objects (<cite>FW</cite> 145.35), schizophrenic personas (<cite>FW</cite> 487.17), perception (<cite>FW</cite> 247.31), and optics (<cite>FW</cite> 349.13), differentiation into genders (<cite>FW</cite> 524.12, <cite>FW</cite> 524.36) and even nuclear physics (<cite>FW</cite> 333.25)] </mm> </dd></dl>
